1 Cluster analysis

First we create the scales to be used in the cluster analysis. Then we run several cluster analyses, elaborate them, and choose the best model. See the datasetup here

library(here)
library(dplyr)
library(misty)
library(factoextra)
library(useful)
library(data.table)
library(cluster)
library(tidyverse)
library(bestNormalize)
library(ggplot2)
library(corrplot)
library(psych)
library(gmodels)


da1 <- read.csv(here("data/processed/korona2020a1.csv"), encoding = 'UTF-8')
dt = as.data.table(da1)
# create subset including classes above 6 (middle school)
dt = dt[class > 6]

Create scales

# count alphas for the scales
a_diff <- alpha.coef(dt[,  c(17:22)], output = FALSE)
a_anxiety <- alpha.coef(dt[, c(53:59)], output = FALSE)
a_teacher <- alpha.coef(dt[, c(82:85)], output = FALSE)
a_peers <- alpha.coef(dt[, c(90:93)], output = FALSE)
a_depr <- alpha.coef(dt[, c(61:66)], output = FALSE)

# extracting results, adding names
scales <- c("diff", "anxiety", "teacher", "peers", "depr")
alphas <- rbind(a_diff$result$alpha[1:2], a_anxiety$result$alpha[1:2],  a_teacher$result$alpha[1:2], a_peers$result$alpha[1:2], a_depr$result$alpha[1:2])
alphas <- cbind (var = scales, alphas)
alphas
##       var items     alpha
## 1    diff     6 0.8706038
## 2 anxiety     7 0.9212885
## 3 teacher     4 0.8496941
## 4   peers     4 0.7608813
## 5    depr     6 0.8664404

Detailed reliability analysis not included here.

Descriptives for the scales

# create dataset for analysis
dtc <- dt[,..scales ]
# Exclude cases with NA
dtc <- dtc[complete.cases(dtc),]

# print descriptives for key variables (= features for clustering)
descript(dt[,..scales], print = c("n", "pNA", "min", "max", "med", "m", "sd"))
##  Variable     n   pNA  Min  Max  Med    M   SD
##  diff     16027 0.00% 0.00 3.00 0.67 0.79 0.65
##  anxiety  16027 0.00% 0.00 3.00 0.43 0.72 0.77
##  teacher  16027 0.00% 0.00 3.00 2.00 1.92 0.62
##  peers    16027 0.00% 0.00 4.00 2.00 2.10 0.96
##  depr     16027 0.00% 1.00 4.00 1.17 1.42 0.59
# plot distributions
dtc %>% keep(is.numeric) %>% gather() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(value)) + facet_wrap(~ key, scales = "free") + geom_density()

# corr matrix
cor_matrix <- cor(dtc) 
# significance tests for corr matrix
res <- cor.mtest(dtc, conf.level = .95)
# draw the corrplot with sig levels
col <- colorRampPalette(c("#BB4444", "#EE9988", "#FFFFFF", "#77AADD", "#4477AA"))
corrplot(cor_matrix, method = "color", col = col(200),
         type = "upper", order = "hclust", number.cex = .7,
         addCoef.col = "grey20", # Add coefficient of correlation
         tl.col = "black", tl.srt = 90, # Text label color and rotation
         # Combine with significance, set visible sig level
         p.mat = res$p, sig.level = 0.01, insig = "blank", 
         # hide correlation coefficient on the principal diagonal
         diag = FALSE)

Prepare clustering

# Exclude cases with NA
dtc <- dtc[complete.cases(dtc),]
# create smaller sample to save time in testing
# dtc <- sample_n(dtc, 1000)

# scale the features
dtc <- as.data.frame(dtc)
dtc <- dtc %>% scale(center = T, scale = T) %>% as.data.frame()

#print descriptives
descript(dtc)
##  Variable     n nNA   pNA     M   SD   Min  Max  Skew  Kurt
##  diff     16027   0 0.00%  0.00 1.00 -1.22 3.40  0.85  0.47
##  anxiety  16027   0 0.00%  0.00 1.00 -0.93 2.96  1.21  0.74
##  teacher  16027   0 0.00% -0.00 1.00 -3.11 1.74 -0.61  1.20
##  peers    16027   0 0.00% -0.00 1.00 -2.18 1.98 -0.17 -0.47
##  depr     16027   0 0.00%  0.00 1.00 -0.72 4.40  1.80  3.13

Variables were scaled for cluster analysis so that different scales donâ€™t affect the output. Only completed cases were included.

Does the dataset have clustering tendency? How to read the output and assess clustering tendency of the data: 1) Hopskin statistics, Scale is 0-1. Close to 0 is highly clusterable, 0.5 is the threshold. 2) PCA, aka. Principal Component Analysis - can you see any clustering in the dots? 3) Dissimilarity matrix of all observations. Objects belonging to the same cluster are displayed in consecutive order. Red: high similarity | Blue: low similarity. Count the number of square shaped dark blocks along the diagonal.

Run clusterings and compare solutions

set.seed(1343)
# run kmeans clustering with different n. of centroids
res.km2 <- eclust(dtc, FUNcluster = "kmeans", hc_metric = "manhattan", k = 2)

res.km3 <- eclust(dtc, FUNcluster = "kmeans", hc_metric = "manhattan", k = 3)

res.km4 <- eclust(dtc, FUNcluster = "kmeans", hc_metric = "manhattan", k = 4)

res.km5 <- eclust(dtc, FUNcluster = "kmeans", hc_metric = "manhattan", k = 5)

The observations are plotted in a two-dimensional space against two principal components. In 5-cluster solution, the principal componentst explain 40,5 + 21,6 = 62,1 % or the variance between observations. No outliers are indentified in the plot.

##   cluster size ave.sil.width
## 1       1 3402          0.11
## 2       2 4660          0.23
## 3       3 1510          0.08
## 4       4 4746          0.26
## 5       5 1709          0.15

  1. Silhouette plot. Each line represents an observation, and each grouping of lines is a cluster. Long positive lines fit in the cluster well, negatives not. A bigger average width means better clustering.

  2. Gap statistics compares the total intracluster variation for different values of k with their expected values under null reference distribution of the data (i.e.Â a distribution with no obvious clustering).

## [1] "Silhoutte stats for 2,3,4,5 cluster solutions"
## [1] 0.3436469 0.2101369 0.2033799 0.1912837
## [1] "EESS% stats for 2,3,4,5 cluster solutions"
## [1] 0.3010124 0.4124239 0.4739059 0.5175061

Interpretation 1: Most troubled: high in internalizing and difficulties in learning, low in teacher relation, average on peers 2: Engaged and happy: low in internalizing and difficulties, high in peer and teacher relations
3: Disconnected but happy: low in peer and teacher relations, average in learning difficulties, low in internalizing

Interpretation: 1: In the middle: some difficulties in learning, high in peer relations, low on internalizing, average in teacher relations 2: Disconnected (same as above) 3: Most troubled (same as above)
4: Engaged and happy (same as above)

How do the five clusters score on different scales? (means)

Interpretation: 1: Troubled but connected: moderately high in troubles with learning and mental health, high in peer relations, average on teacher

2: Isolated from peers: low on peer relations. Low in troubles with learning or with mental health. Teacher relations above average.

3: Disconnected: low on peer and teacher relations, above average on learning, average on internalizing

4: Engaged and happy: low in internalizing and difficulties, high in peer and teacher relations

5: Most troubled: high in internalizing and difficulties in learning, low in teacher relations, quite low on peers

Kruskal and Wilcox tests

dt %>% select(one_of(c('class', 'diff', 'peers', 'teacher', 'anxiety', 'depr', 'timeuse'))) %>% group_by(class) %>% summarise_all("mean")
## # A tibble: 3 x 7
##   class  diff peers teacher anxiety  depr timeuse
##   <int> <dbl> <dbl>   <dbl>   <dbl> <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1     7 0.762  2.13    1.97   0.663  1.40    3.96
## 2     8 0.815  2.08    1.90   0.700  1.41    4.05
## 3     9 0.811  2.08    1.90   0.803  1.45    4.12
kruskal.test(teacher ~ class, data = dt)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  teacher by class
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 39.419, df = 2, p-value = 2.756e-09
kruskal.test(Cluster ~ timeusec, data = dt)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  Cluster by timeusec
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 59.123, df = 20, p-value = 9.727e-06
pairwise.wilcox.test(dt$timeusec, dt$Cluster, p.adjust.method = "BH")

Correlations

library(corrplot)
external <- c('class', 'timeuse', 'timeusec', 'likesch', 'peers', 'diff')
# create dataset for analysis
dte <- dt[,..external ]
# Exclude cases with NA
dte <- dte[complete.cases(dte),]

# corr matrix
cor_matrix2 <- cor(dte) 
# significance tests for corr matrix
res2 <- cor.mtest(dte, method="pearson", conf.level = .95)
# draw the corrplot with sig levels
col <- colorRampPalette(c("#BB4444", "#EE9988", "#FFFFFF", "#77AADD", "#4477AA"))
corrplot(cor_matrix2, method = "color", col = col(200),
         type = "upper", order = "hclust", number.cex = .7,
         addCoef.col = "grey20", # Add coefficient of correlation
         tl.col = "black", tl.srt = 90, # Text label color and rotation
         # Combine with significance, set visible sig level
         p.mat = res2$p, sig.level = 0.05, insig = "blank", 
         # hide correlation coefficient on the principal diagonal
         diag = FALSE)

# show the p-value
